Skip the "Do you wish to save your new configuration?" dialog when
the user hasn't toggled anything during the interactive session.

Busybox 1.36.1's mconf (scripts/kconfig/mconf.c:1088) always prompts
on exit, regardless of whether the user actually changed anything.
Modern Linux mconf gates that same block on sym_change_count; port
the check here.

Subtle detail, also patched: conf_read() itself bumps
sym_change_count via conf_unsaved when a loaded .config value
differs from Kconfig's computed default (see confdata.c:297-326).
For our flow that's pre-session noise: run_config seeds .config
from the sidecar's current values, which are exactly what the
user's cache already holds. Reset sym_change_count to zero after
conf_read so the prompt truly reflects "user made changes in this
session".

--- a/scripts/kconfig/mconf.c
+++ b/scripts/kconfig/mconf.c
@@ -1069,6 +1069,16 @@
 	conf_parse(av[1]);
 	conf_read(NULL);
 
+	/*
+	 * Tilck patch: conf_read() already bumps sym_change_count
+	 * via conf_unsaved when a loaded .config value differs from
+	 * Kconfig's computed default. For run_config's flow that is
+	 * pre-session noise (we seed .config from the sidecar every
+	 * launch), so reset here; the save-on-exit check below then
+	 * only reflects user-driven changes.
+	 */
+	sym_change_count = 0;
+
 	sym = sym_lookup("KERNELVERSION", 0);
 	sym_calc_value(sym);
 	sprintf(menu_backtitle, _("BusyBox %s Configuration"),
@@ -1085,6 +1095,14 @@
 	init_wsize();
 	conf(&rootmenu);
 
+	/*
+	 * Tilck patch (see sym_change_count = 0 above): skip the
+	 * save dialog if the user did not toggle any option during
+	 * this interactive session.
+	 */
+	if (!sym_change_count)
+		return 0;
+
 	do {
 		cprint_init();
 		cprint("--yesno");
